schema.title: A compute node in the Batch service.

affinityId.title: An identifier which can be passed when adding a task to request that the task be scheduled on this node.
affinityId.description: Note that this is just a soft affinity. If the target node is busy or unavailable at the time the task is scheduled, then the task will be scheduled elsewhere.

allocationTime.title: The time at which this compute node was allocated to the pool.

certificateReferences.title: The list of certificates installed on the compute node.
certificateReferences.description: For Windows compute nodes, the Batch service installs the certificates to the specified certificate store and location. For Linux compute nodes, the certificates are stored in a directory inside the task working directory and an environment variable AZ_BATCH_CERTIFICATES_DIR is supplied to the task to query for this location. For certificates with visibility of 'remoteUser', a 'certs' directory is created in the user's home directory (e.g., /home/{user-name}/certs) and certificates are placed in that directory.

errors.title: The list of errors that are currently being encountered by the compute node.

id.title: The ID of the compute node.
id.description: Every node that is added to a pool is assigned a unique ID. Whenever a node is removed from a pool, all of its local files are deleted, and the ID is reclaimed and could be reused for new nodes.

ipAddress.title: The IP address that other compute nodes can use to communicate with this compute node.
ipAddress.description: Every node that is added to a pool is assigned a unique IP address. Whenever a node is removed from a pool, all of its local files are deleted, and the IP address is reclaimed and could be reused for new nodes.

isDedicated.title: Whether this compute node is a dedicated node. If false, the node is a low-priority node.

lastBootTime.title: The time at which the compute node was started.
lastBootTime.description: This property may not be present if the node state is unusable.

recentTasks.title: A list of tasks whose state has recently changed.
recentTasks.description: This property is present only if at least one task has run on this node since it was assigned to the pool.

runningTasksCount.title: The total number of currently running job tasks on the compute node. This includes Job Manager tasks and normal tasks, but not Job Preparation, Job Release or Start tasks.

schedulingState.title: Whether the compute node is available for task scheduling.

state.title: The current state of the compute node.
state.description: The low-priority node has been preempted. Tasks which were running on the node when it was preempted will be rescheduled when another node becomes available.

stateTransitionTime.title: The time at which the compute node entered its current state.

totalTasksRun.title: The total number of job tasks completed on the compute node. This includes Job Manager tasks and normal tasks, but not Job Preparation, Job Release or Start tasks.

totalTasksSucceeded.title: The total number of job tasks which completed successfully (with exitCode 0) on the compute node. This includes Job Manager tasks and normal tasks, but not Job Preparation, Job Release or Start tasks.

url.title: The URL of the compute node.

vmSize.title: The size of the virtual machine hosting the compute node.
vmSize.description: For information about available sizes of virtual machines in pools, see Choose a VM size for compute nodes in an Azure Batch pool (https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/batch/batch-pool-vm-sizes).

schema.title: A pool in the Azure Batch service.

allocationStateTransitionTime.title: The time at which the pool entered its current allocation state.

applicationLicenses.title: The list of application licenses the Batch service will make available on each compute node in the pool.
applicationLicenses.description: The list of application licenses must be a subset of available Batch service application licenses. If a license is requested which is not supported, pool creation will fail.

applicationPackageReferences.title: The list of application packages to be installed on each compute node in the pool.

autoScaleEvaluationInterval.title: The time interval at which to automatically adjust the pool size according to the autoscale formula.
autoScaleEvaluationInterval.description: This property is set only if the pool automatically scales, i.e. enableAutoScale is true.

autoScaleFormula.title: A formula for the desired number of compute nodes in the pool.
autoScaleFormula.description: This property is set only if the pool automatically scales, i.e. enableAutoScale is true.

certificateReferences.title: The list of certificates to be installed on each compute node in the pool.
certificateReferences.description: For Windows compute nodes, the Batch service installs the certificates to the specified certificate store and location. For Linux compute nodes, the certificates are stored in a directory inside the task working directory and an environment variable AZ_BATCH_CERTIFICATES_DIR is supplied to the task to query for this location. For certificates with visibility of 'remoteUser', a 'certs' directory is created in the user's home directory (e.g., /home/{user-name}/certs) and certificates are placed in that directory.

creationTime.title: The creation time of the pool.

currentDedicatedNodes.title: The number of dedicated compute nodes currently in the pool.

currentLowPriorityNodes.title: The number of low-priority compute nodes currently in the pool.
currentLowPriorityNodes.description: Low-priority compute nodes which have been preempted are included in this count.

displayName.title: The display name for the pool.
displayName.description: The display name need not be unique and can contain any Unicode characters up to a maximum length of 1024.

eTag.title: The ETag of the pool.
eTag.description: This is an opaque string. You can use it to detect whether the pool has changed between requests. In particular, you can be pass the ETag when updating a pool to specify that your changes should take effect only if nobody else has modified the pool in the meantime.

enableAutoScale.title: Whether the pool size should automatically adjust over time.
enableAutoScale.description: If false, at least one of targetDedicateNodes and targetLowPriorityNodes must be specified. If true, the autoScaleFormula property is required and the pool automatically resizes according to the formula. The default value is false.

enableInterNodeCommunication.title: Whether the pool permits direct communication between nodes.
enableInterNodeCommunication.description: This imposes restrictions on which nodes can be assigned to the pool. Specifying this value can reduce the chance of the requested number of nodes to be allocated in the pool.

id.title: A string that uniquely identifies the pool within the account.
id.description: The ID can contain any combination of alphanumeric characters including hyphens and underscores, and cannot contain more than 64 characters. The ID is case-preserving and case-insensitive (that is, you may not have two IDs within an account that differ only by case).

lastModified.title: The last modified time of the pool.
lastModified.description: This is the last time at which the pool level data, such as the targetDedicatedNodes or enableAutoscale settings, changed. It does not factor in node-level changes such as a compute node changing state.

maxTasksPerNode.title: The maximum number of tasks that can run concurrently on a single compute node in the pool.

metadata.title: A list of name-value pairs associated with the pool as metadata.

resizeErrors.title: A list of errors encountered while performing the last resize on the pool.
resizeErrors.description: This property is set only if one or more errors occurred during the last pool resize, and only when the pool allocationState is Steady.

resizeTimeout.title: The timeout for allocation of compute nodes to the pool.
resizeTimeout.description: This is the timeout for the most recent resize operation. (The initial sizing when the pool is created counts as a resize.) The default value is 15 minutes.

state.title: The current state of the pool.

stateTransitionTime.title: The time at which the pool entered its current state.

targetDedicatedNodes.title: The desired number of dedicated compute nodes in the pool.

targetLowPriorityNodes.title: The desired number of low-priority compute nodes in the pool.

userAccounts.title: The list of user accounts to be created on each node in the pool.

vmSize.title: The size of virtual machines in the pool. All virtual machines in a pool are the same size.
vmSize.description: For information about available sizes of virtual machines in pools, see Choose a VM size for compute nodes in an Azure Batch pool (https://docs.microsoft.com/azure/batch/batch-pool-vm-sizes).

schema.title: Contains utilization and resource usage statistics for the lifetime of a pool.

lastUpdateTime.title: The time at which the statistics were last updated. All statistics are limited to the range between startTime and lastUpdateTime.

mappings.name: Gets lifetime summary statistics for all of the jobs in the specified account.

schema.title: Resource usage statistics for a job.

kernelCPUTime.title: The total kernel mode CPU time (summed across all cores and all compute nodes) consumed by all tasks in the job.

lastUpdateTime.title: The time at which the statistics were last updated. All statistics are limited to the range between startTime and lastUpdateTime.

numFailedTasks.title: The total number of tasks in the job that failed during the given time range.
numFailedTasks.description: A task fails if it exhausts its maximum retry count without returning exit code 0.

numSucceededTasks.title: The total number of tasks successfully completed in the job during the given time range.
numSucceededTasks.description: A task completes successfully if it returns exit code 0.

numTaskRetries.title: The total number of retries on all the tasks in the job during the given time range.

readIOGiB.title: The total amount of data in GiB read from disk by all tasks in the job.

readIOps.title: The total number of disk read operations made by all tasks in the job.

startTime.title: The start time of the time range covered by the statistics.

userCPUTime.title: The total user mode CPU time (summed across all cores and all compute nodes) consumed by all tasks in the job.

waitTime.title: The total wait time of all tasks in the job.
waitTime.description: The wait time for a task is defined as the elapsed time between the creation of the task and the start of task execution. (If the task is retried due to failures, the wait time is the time to the most recent task execution.) This value is only reported in the account lifetime statistics; it is not included in the job statistics.

wallClockTime.title: The total wall clock time of all tasks in the job.
wallClockTime.description: The wall clock time is the elapsed time from when the task started running on a compute node to when it finished (or to the last time the statistics were updated, if the task had not finished by then). If a task was retried, this includes the wall clock time of all the task retries.

writeIOGiB.title: The total amount of data in GiB written to disk by all tasks in the job.

writeIOps.title: The total number of disk write operations made by all tasks in the job.

schema.title: An Azure Batch task.

applicationPackageReferences.title: A list of application packages that the Batch service will deploy to the compute node before running the command line.
applicationPackageReferences.description: Application packages are downloaded and deployed to a shared directory, not the task working directory. Therefore, if a referenced package is already on the compute node, and is up to date, then it is not re-downloaded; the existing copy on the compute node is used. If a referenced application package cannot be installed, for example because the package has been deleted or because download failed, the task fails.

commandLine.title: The command line of the task.
commandLine.description: For multi-instance tasks, the command line is executed as the primary task, after the primary task and all subtasks have finished executing the coordination command line. The command line does not run under a shell, and therefore cannot take advantage of shell features such as environment variable expansion. If you want to take advantage of such features, you should invoke the shell in the command line, for example using "cmd /c MyCommand" in Windows or "/bin/sh -c MyCommand" in Linux. If the command line refers to file paths, it should use a relative path (relative to the task working directory), or use the Batch provided environment variable (https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/batch/batch-compute-node-environment-variables).

creationTime.title: The creation time of the task.

displayName.title: A display name for the task.
displayName.description: The display name need not be unique and can contain any Unicode characters up to a maximum length of 1024.

eTag.title: The ETag of the task.
eTag.description: This is an opaque string. You can use it to detect whether the task has changed between requests. In particular, you can be pass the ETag when updating a task to specify that your changes should take effect only if nobody else has modified the task in the meantime.

environmentSettings.title: A list of environment variable settings for the task.

id.title: A string that uniquely identifies the task within the job.
id.description: The ID can contain any combination of alphanumeric characters including hyphens and underscores, and cannot contain more than 64 characters.

lastModified.title: The last modified time of the task.

outputFiles.title: A list of files that the Batch service will upload from the compute node after running the command line.
outputFiles.description: For multi-instance tasks, the files will only be uploaded from the compute node on which the primary task is executed.

previousStateTransitionTime.title: The time at which the task entered its previous state.
previousStateTransitionTime.description: This property is not set if the task is in its initial Active state.

resourceFiles.title: A list of files that the Batch service will download to the compute node before running the command line.
resourceFiles.description: For multi-instance tasks, the resource files will only be downloaded to the compute node on which the primary task is executed. There is a maximum size for the list of resource files.  When the max size is exceeded, the request will fail and the response error code will be RequestEntityTooLarge. If this occurs, the collection of ResourceFiles must be reduced in size. This can be achieved using .zip files, Application Packages, or Docker Containers.

stateTransitionTime.title: The time at which the task entered its current state.

schema.description: Batch will retry tasks when a recovery operation is triggered on a compute node. Examples of recovery operations include (but are not limited to) when an unhealthy compute node is rebooted or a compute node disappeared due to host failure. Retries due to recovery operations are independent of and are not counted against the maxTaskRetryCount. Even if the maxTaskRetryCount is 0, an internal retry due to a recovery operation may occur. Because of this, all tasks should be idempotent. This means tasks need to tolerate being interrupted and restarted without causing any corruption or duplicate data. The best practice for long running tasks is to use some form of checkpointing.

displayName.title: The display name for the job.

eTag.title: The ETag of the job.
eTag.description: This is an opaque string. You can use it to detect whether the job has changed between requests. In particular, you can be pass the ETag when updating a job to specify that your changes should take effect only if nobody else has modified the job in the meantime.

id.title: A string that uniquely identifies the job within the account.
id.description: The ID is case-preserving and case-insensitive (that is, you may not have two IDs within an account that differ only by case).

lastModified.title: The last modified time of the job.
lastModified.description: This is the last time at which the job level data, such as the job state or priority, changed. It does not factor in task-level changes such as adding new tasks or tasks changing state.

metadata.title: A list of name-value pairs associated with the job as metadata.
metadata.description: The Batch service does not assign any meaning to metadata; it is solely for the use of user code.

previousStateTransitionTime.title: The time at which the job entered its previous state.
previousStateTransitionTime.description: This property is not set if the job is in its initial Active state.

priority.title: The priority of the job.
priority.description: Priority values can range from -1000 to 1000, with -1000 being the lowest priority and 1000 being the highest priority. The default value is 0.

usesTaskDependencies.title: Whether tasks in the job can define dependencies on each other. The default is false.
